<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN369">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>iruppumukañ ceṟitta vēnteḻiṉ maruppiṟ</l>
<l>karuṅkai yāṉai koṇmū vāka</l>
<l>nīṇmoḻi maṟava reṟivaṉa ruyartta</l>
<l>vāṇmiṉ ṉāka vayaṅkukaṭip pamainta</l>
<l>kurutip paliya muracumuḻak kāka</l>
<l>varacarāp paṉikku maṇaṅkuṟu poḻutiṉ</l>
<l>vevvicaip puravi vīcuvaḷi yāka</l>
<l>vicaippuṟu valvil vīṅkunā ṇukaitta</l>
<l>kaṇaittuḷi poḻinta kaṇṇakaṉ kiṭakkai</l>
<l>yīrac ceṟuvayiṟ ṟērē rāka</l>
<l>viṭiyal pukku neṭiya nīṭṭiniṉ</l>
<l>ceruppaṭai miḷirtta tiruttuṟu paiñcāṟ</l>
<l>piṭitteṟi veḷvēl kaṇaiyamoṭu vitti</l>
<l>viḻuttalai cāytta veruvaru paiṅkūḻp</l>
<l>pēymakaḷ paṟṟiya piṇampiṟaṅku palpōrpu</l>
<l>kaṇanari yōṭu kaḻutukaḷam paṭuppap</l>
<l>pūtaṅ kāppap polikaḷan taḻīip</l>
<l>pāṭunark kirunta pīṭuṭai yāḷa</l>
<l>tēyvai veṇkāḻ puraiyum vicipiṇi</l>
<l>vēyvai kāṇā viruntiṟ pōrvai</l>
<l>yarikkuraṟ ṟaṭāri yuruppa voṟṟip</l>
<l>pāṭi vanticiṟ peruma pāṭāṉ</l>
<l>ṟeḻili tōyu mimiḻicai yaruvip</l>
<l>poṉṉuṭai neṭuṅkōṭ ṭimayat taṉṉa</l>
<l>vōṭai nutala volkuta laṟiyāt</l>
<l>tuṭiyaṭik kuḻaviya piṭiyiṭai miṭainta</l>
<l>vēḻa mukavai nalkumati</l>
<l>tāḻā vīkait takaivey yōyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Black-trunked elephants with eminent graceful tusks,</l>
<l>on which iron face[-masks are tightened, as clouds,</l>
<l>swords that are raised by fighting valorous men of</l>
<l>long[-lasting] word as lightning, drums, that have been offered blood,</l>
<l>subjected to glowing drum sticks, as thunder,</l>
<l>horses of hot speed at the tormenting time,</l>
<l>when lordly snakes tremble, as gushing wind,</l>
<l>the chariots on the wet field, an expanse of wide area,</l>
<l>flown by drops: arrows discharged by the bulging string</l>
<l>of the speedy strong bow, as ploughs,</l>
<l>prolonging for a long time when dawn had entered,</l>
<l>sowing white spears, thrown after gripping [them], along with arrows</l>
<l>into the well-prepared fresh furrows thrown up by your fighting weapon,</l>
<l>joining the flourishing [battle] field while Bhūtas stand guard,</l>
<l>to establish a threshing floor, for demons along with jackals in groups,</l>
<l>of many heaps of corspses, seized by Pēy demonesses,</l>
<l>for frightening fresh crops, on which the excellent heads are bent,</l>
<l>– o man full of greatness, who remained for the singers!</l>
<l>Come, o great one, singing,</l>
<l>pressing the Taṭāri drum with tinkling voice so that the covering</l>
<l>burns, on the feast where no defect is seen,</l>
<l>with tied fetters, resembling the dwindling white core.</l>
<l>The songs having ended,</l>
<l>please grant gifts of elephant bulls</l>
<l>set in between Tuṭi-drum-footed elephant cows with calfs,</l>
<l>not knowing of becoming weak, foreheads with metal plates,</l>
<l>like the Himalaya with golden long peaks</l>
<l>[and] waterfalls of buzzing sound that touch the clouds,</l>
<l>o you who is keen on what is befitting [in the line of] undeclining giving.</l>
</lg>
